@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
		     @{fg shine}-= From The Editor's Desk =-
		          @{fg text} by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}

It seems like it was only a few weeks ago that I was sitting here writing
the 'From The Editor's Desk' for issue 4, but that was now over two months
ago and a lot has happened in that time.  As you may have already noticed
the magazine has moved to a bi-monthly format, while it had been my 
initial intention of producing the magazine in a monthly format, the lack
of time afforded by myself and the other writers meant that it became a
difficult task to accomplish each month.  It was compounded also by the
fact that the magazine does not deal with gaming, which means less reviews 
and guides.  However with the newer format we will hopefully be able to 
provide more indepth articles, reviews and tutorials.  

For this issue it is my great pleasure to welcome Maddi a.k.a MsMadLemon 
to the magazine, she has her first article in the form of a tracking 
tutorial and an interview.  In fact this issue we have two interviews, 
the other being with Karl Jeacle the author of AmiGemini.  The reviews 
and guides have been my sole job this issue due to time constraints of 
John Scolieri and Steve Lord however fingers crossed they will have more 
time for the next issue out in August.  Kevin Saunders continues his usual 
column, Invent's Corner, talking about the new Amiga Art Contest 2022.

I have decided to remove the news section due to the change to a bi-monthly
format.  Most of the news will have been old by the time the magazine is 
released and I thought it might be better used as a soapbox column or as
it called  Shell Talk, John Scolieri is doing the honours with an article
about Amiga OS on a x86 hardware.  Well I will not take up anymore of your
time, I just want to thank all the contributors for this issue and you the
reader.  In addition, to help fund the magazine I have added a donation
button to the www.whatiff.info website, this will help with the running of
the magazine and help in paying a little bit towards the efforts of the
writers.  For this issue I want thank: Christopher White and Anthony 
Jarvis for their kind donations to the magazine.  

As always if you have any comments or want to contribute to the magazine 
please send an e-mail to: submissions@whatiff.info

Thank you for taking the time to download and read this magazine, I hope
that you enjoy it and find the content useful.  Until next time! 
@endnode

@node shelltalk "Free For All About The Amiga"
@toc contents
		          @{fg shine}-= Shell Talk =-@{fg text}
		          Written by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}

 - = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = -
RANT...why not port AmigaOS to x86 hardware?

Without fail every year since Commodore went bankrupt in 1994 and new 
ownership seemed to make promise after promise about new hardware to run 
Amiga OS there's been rumblings about the cheap and easily available PC's 
of the time and why should amigans wait for new hardware and why not just 
run AmigaOS on the cheap PC's of the time?

Simple enough question back then right? Well...the new owners in the late 
90's were Haage & Partner (H&P) and Amiga users were losing patience with 
the direction of their favourite computer and OS. They were working on 
OS3.9 at the time for existing Amiga computers while entertaining the idea 
of running a QNX backend and emulating AmigaOS on top of it. 
The alternative was an Amiga running on PC(x86) hardware called AmigaOS XL 
and promising all future hardware problems would be solved.

The Amiga community seemed ok with this direction at first BUT H&P's 
PC(x86) hardware was the opposite of affordable and made an Amiga 4000 
Tower look really cheap! Luckily Amiga developers figured out a way to get 
cheaper off the shelf PCs to run AmigaOS XL (later named Amithlon) 
but alas the start of legal issues was just around the corner as Amiga 
Inc. had an issue with H&P regarding some embedded files on the AmigaOS XL 
CD which was the intellectual property of Amiga Inc., ultimately this 
would stop the sale of it in the early 2000's.

This didn't stop some Amigans from developing Amithlon to run on different 
motherboards and updating the QNX kernal but without the support of H&P 
and Amiga Inc. due to the legal issues AmigaOS XL/ Amithlon didn't 
reach the main stream potential it was originally aimed for. There are 
still users today running AmigaOS XL/Amithlon systems but it's a pretty 
complicated setup process with very specific hardware requirements and 
it's been quite a while now that emulation packages such as Amikit and 
Cloanto's AmigaForever easily allows even the most technically challenged
user to install and run modern verisons of AmigaOS on any possible x86 
hardware avialable even on the inexpensive Raspberry Pie.

So why is the Amiga community still today divided about porting AmigaOS to 
x86 hardware then? There's a group of users that are happy to use original 
hardware and keep the spirit of AmigaOS and 68K Motorolla CPU's today by 
creating new games and software. There's a group that says the old 
hardware is getting even older, rarer and more expensive to keep going 
with every passing year. There's another group that is using FPGA 
technology to improve on the original OS and improve it with more modern 
features. 

Theres another group that uses the PPC version of Amiga OS4.1 on dedicated 
PPC hardware and another group using existing old Apple PPC hardware to 
run MorphOS (AmigaOS 'like'OS) and lastly there's another group that uses 
AROS (an open source Amiga implemantation at the API level aiming to be 
compatible with AmigaOS programs) on specific available X86 hardware. 

The way I see it is that I have no idea why the topic comes up all the 
time? We already have AROS which is free to use and open source to use on 
specific modern PC hardware.  The current PPC options of AmigaOS and 
MorphOS have invested countless developer/testing hours on specific PPC 
hardware and it would require infinite more time and resources to port to 
x86 hardware and honestly I don't believe that even if it miraculously 
would happen I doubt that sales would drastically increase(that is if 
never ending lawsuits would allow it sigh). The FPGA crowd can run AROS or 
AmigaOS so there's no issue there. Emulation via UAE is getting better and 
better every year for even the casual Amiga user that wants to roll down
nostlgia lane even for a little while can easily be up and running within 
minutes. 

Today Amiga users have all kinds of choices to run their favourite OS in 
one shape or another. There are dedicated developers for each user group 
and many times I see co-operation between developers and users of different 
groups. Of course there's the usual 'disagreements' between groups but 
overall we are truly lucky to have new software and games coming out quite
regularly for all AmigaOS options avalable today!

Juat don't be surpised when you see this topic come up again next year :-)

Rant over.
cheers,
G. Scolieri

@endnode

