@node framemeisterreview "Framemiester X-RGB Review"
@toc reviews
	   	@{b}@{fg fill}*Framemeister X-RGB Review - April 2022*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
Micomsoft Framemeister XRGB Mini

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Available From@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
www.solarisjapan.com or ebay
JPY 50,000

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
EURO SCART Adapter Cable

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Commodore Amiga 1200

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Little Box Of Wonders@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
For those of you who are serious about their retro gaming with orginal
hardware the Frameisters will most likely be on your radar.  Those of
you who are not aware of the Framemeister please let me explain a little
about this wonderful black box.  The Framemeister was made (since it is
out of production now) by the Japanese company Micomsoft, they have a
long history of making scandoublers/upscalers for older hardware and the
Framemeister is it's best known product.  The Meisters are known
for their reduced input lag, outstanding image quality, and wide variety 
of visual and audio settings.  The Framemeisters before the XRGB Mini were 
large and expensive though they did sport several SCART inputs allowing 
more than one device to plugged in at a time.  In 2011 Micomsoft released
the XRGB Mini, a much smaller, lighter device that soon became their best
selling product.  The original asking price was 50,000 Japanese Yen and
since then the prices have been going up.  However it is still possible to
buy new Framemeisters from the Japanese resller Solaris for around 53,000
Japanese Yen.  This is not cheap by any means but as you will find out 
later there is a good reason for this price.

The XRGB Mini comes with several inputs: AV, S-Video and RGB (SCART), you 
can also add 2 HDMI inputs, so it is possible to use your Bluray player or 
modern console with the XRGB Mini as an HDMI switcher.  The unit comes 
with a Japanese SCART cable but it is recommended to buy a European SCART 
cable and one with a sync cable.  I did this at the time of purchase
since all my SCART cables are European even though I am using Japanese 
hardware.  Alongside the SCART cable, you get a remote and power supply, 
the remote is in Japanese so for those unable to read Japanese I suggest
buying an overlay with English translation of the buttons.    

Before using my Amiga with the Framemeister I had used it with several 
Japanese consoles: Super Famicom, Megadrive, PC Engine, N64, PC-FX and
Sega Saturn.  All of these consoles output a beautiful crisp and bright
picture, with the added scanlines it took me right back to playing on
my old CRT TV, but this time the TV was 50 inches instead of 14.  It is
difficult to describe how much of a difference the XRGB Mini made to the
gameplay experience, it was the first time in over 10 years since I had
seen such a crisp picture on a modern TV.  Although there is apparently
input lag, I did not notice this during game play, though it could be
down to my slower reactions.  The only console that I had a little issue
with was the Super Famicom, the original SCART cable was not a true RGB
cable and as such the picture was quite dark and there was a buzzing 
sound present.  After a quick search on eBay I found a true RGB SCART
cable for the Super Famicom, once the cable arrived it was startling
the difference.  The Super Famicom picture was bright and crisp with no
buzzing sound either.  So after having used the XRGB with my consoles
I started to think maybe it might be a good fit with the Amiga.  Find
out below to see if this just might be the box to fix all your upscaling
needs.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Amiga 1200 Meet Framemeister@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}   
The beauty of the Framemeister is that it is ready for SCART input and can
handle NSTC and PAL with ease, as such hooking up the A1200 to the XRGB 
Mini was easy with a standard RGB SCART cable.  The XRGB can handle 240p
but anything above that and it will not work, so the Amiga is limited to
HiRes Laced PAL/NTSC, any of the other screenmodes and the upscaler will
not accept the signal.  If you use your Amiga primarily for games this
should not be an issue.

The XRGB produced a sharp and bright image from the A1200, it looked much 
better than I had expected.  The only niggle I could see was a blurring on
the mouse pointer when moved.  It is not a big issue however it was not 
noticable when using an Indivision.  I am not sure why it does this, but
when I run the XRGB with scanlines on my TV and play a scrolling shooter
the scanlines seem to disapear, I wonder if this is a possible setting 
issue as there is much that can be changed on the Framemesiter, or it 
could be an issue of my TV.

The next issue is a bit more frustrating and exposes the limitations of 
the XRGB, if you stay in the same resolution of PAL/NTSC LoRes/HiRes the
XRGB will have no issues, however if you change to a higher resolution 
such as Hires Laced the Framemeister takes a long time to change 
resolution, it is long enough for you to start worrying something might
have gone wrong.  Other than these two issues the XRGB allows you to use
your Amiga on a modern monitor along with other retro computer/consoles.
However if you wish to use the AGA chipset's more advanced resolutions 
then the Framemeister XRGB Mini is not the scandoubler for you.  I did
check the scandoubler with other software such as Final Write, Brilliance
Lightwave, OctaMED and found the image quality to be superb as long as
I did not stray from the default Amiga resolutions.  The picture is rock
solid and very clear coming close to that of the Indivision.  

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Final Thoughts@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
The Framemeister XRGB Mini has gained a legendary status as the upscaler
for playing older consoles on modern TVs.  It rightly deserves the 
reputation, while it is far from being cheap it allows you to enjoy most
of your 80s and early 90s retro consoles and computers in beautiful RGB
with scanlines.  The Amiga is supported by the XRGB Mini but only if you
stay within the 240p resolutions of NTSC/PAL Hires/Lores screen modes.

If you want one box for all your retro gear then the Framemeister is the
device for you.  It is more expensive than the OSS open source scandoubler
but it provides you with a slightly better picture quality and more IO
options.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Pros and Cons@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
+ Beautiful picture quality
+ Scanlines done properly
+ Not limited to Amiga computers
- Expensive
- Limited resolutions supported
- Only available from Japan
@endnode

@node scarttohdmireview "SCART to HDMI Review"
@toc reviews
 	    	  @{b}@{fg fill}*SCARt to HDMI Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
SCART to HDMI Scandoubler

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Available From@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
eBay
Price: £15.00-50.00

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Hardware Requirements@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
SCART and HDMI Cables 

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Commodore Amiga 1200
Classic WB + 3.2 Kickstart
TF 1260 
  
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}A Cheap Alternative To The Indivision@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Getting the Amiga connected to a modern device can be a quite a struggle
at times, and more so it can become increasingly expensive.  Over the last
few years there have been devices popping up on auction sites such as eBay
advertising SCART to HDMI scandoublers for an average price of £30.  In 
most cases they are generic devices made in China and are easy to get hold
of.  A device that takes in the Amiga's RGB signal and upscales it to HDMI
for the price of an Amiga game seems a little too good to be true, so I 
invested in one for myself to see how well these little boxes fare.

The device itself is very small, smaller than a CD case, has one SCART 
input and HDMI output, there is an audio out port and custom power cable 
that ends in a USB plug.  In addition there are buttons for PAL/NSTC and 
for changing the output resolution from 480p, 720p up to 1080p.  Setup is 
very easy as all you need is a standard Amiga SCART cable and then an
HDMI cable to connect to your display.  The device quickly picked up the
signal from the Amiga and up popped my Workbench.  First impressions were
good, it looked relatively clean with minor ghosting around the edges of
windows, however upon opening a window I noticed the white balance was on
the extreme side with the colours looking washed out.  The mouse pointer
also had a shimmering effect when moved.  This seemed to include anything
that moved on the screen, causing the screen to have a blurred look when
in movement.

For me the ultimate test is using Brilliance for some pixel pushing and 
unfortunately the scandoubler did not produce a result that I was happy
with.  It was difficult to see the individual pixels due to heavy blurring
making it impossible to do any decent artwork.  I tried to change the
settings and monitor but still came up with a picture quality that was
not acceptable for my situation.  Over time the box became quite hot and
the picture disapeared a few times, turning green and purple.  It is clear
this scandoubler is not suitable for long computer sessions.

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Final Thoughts@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}    
The SCART to HDMI scandoubler fits a segement of users who are on a 
limited budget and are more concerned about using their Amiga for 
games.  While I would find it frustrating to play games on the device
it is still better than using the built in upscalers in modern televions.
If you want to do word processing, graphics or something productive I
would suggest saving up for an Indivision or similar card.  It is a nice
product for the price, but you get what you pay for and as such do not
expect something that can handle all Amiga resolutions or give you a
pixel perfect image.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Pros and Cons@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
+ Easy to use
+ Cheap
- Average to poor video quality
- Not able to be used for long periods of time
@endnode

@node clovericonsreview "CloverIcons Review"
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*CloverIcons Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
CloverIcons

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Aminet

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Special Hardware and Software Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Any Amiga / Amiga OS 2.0.4+

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Machine Used For Testing@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Commodore Amiga 1200
Kickstart 3.2
ClassicWB
Indivision MK3, TF1260

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Clover Icons Review@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
As Amiga users we are luckly to have a system that can easily be tailored 
to our tastes, it is a stark contrast to the modern OSes out from 
Microsoft and Apple which do not allow much of any customisation.  Over 
the years various iconsets have come and gone with MagicWB and NewIcons 
being the most used and recognised.  Of recent GlowIcons has become part 
of the new newer Amiga OS but like NewIcons it really benefits from a 
high colour and resolution dispay.  Where as MagicWB provides a metalic 8 
colour alternative, great for the lower spec Amigas.  What has not been 
released however is a 4 colour icon replacement set, one that will take up 
the least amount of resources and provide a new lick of paint freshening
up the default Workbench icons, until now that is.  During my daily search 
on Aminet I came across Clover Icons, a low resource, 4 colour icon 
replacement.  

@{fg shine}@{b}@{u}Why would you want a 4 colour icon set?@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  

If you are running stock Amiga hardware without any expansions you are 
limited by what iconsets you can use, as such this is where Clover 
Icons steps up.  The basic icon set is reminiscent of Workbench 2.0/3.0 
but look a bit closer and you will see there is more detail and variety 
to the icons than the vanilla WB icons.  The drawers and disk icons in 
particular look quite nice even though they only use 4 colours.  The 
Preferences, Tools and Utilities icons look very similar to the default 
icons but still have enough new detail to make Workbench look 
that much more fetching.

The package comes with an installer for installing the basic Workbench 
icons and default icons along with some extra drawers and programmes.
There is an additional package available on Aminet with more icons for 
drawers and various programmes.  At the moment the selection is quite 
small but hopefully other icon artists will provide some more icon sets.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Should You Change Your Icons?@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
If you are looking for a change to the default icons and do not want to
use up many resources then this icon set is for you.  It creates a more
modern looking Workbench without the overheads that other icon 
replacements come with.  They are made for being used without borders so
look very nice when used as such.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}			  
+ Comes with a proper installer for all icons
+ Low overhead		   
+ Made with borderless icons in mind
- Lack of other icons                                  
- Too similar looking to the default Workbench icons
@endnode

@node annoreview
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*Anno Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
Anno: Reminder and calendar utility version 2.5

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
www.aminet.net/package/util/time/Anno
Created by: Juergen Klawitter

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Never Forget Another Appointment@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
I am quite the forgetful person, so I often write even small events in my
diary to help me keep on track of things.  While it is great to have a
physical schedule book it would be nice to have the computer remind me.
So it was with considerable interest that I spotted Anno on the recent 
uploads page of Aminet.  The text describes it as a 'Reminder and Calendar
Utility', and appears to the full programme.  It comes in at only 300kb so
will be an easy download to an Amiga.

Once unpacked the drawer contains 2 guides in English and German, 2 example
pictures in English and German, plus the programme.  I suggest reading the
guide first as the programme is not that user friendly, upon bringing up 
the programme for the first time you presented with an empty window 
displaying the current date of your computer.  At the bottom are some 
buttons but they only have single letters on them making it a bit hard to
figure out what each one does.  However each button is explained in the
guide but I feel that it could have been made a bit more explicit what 
each button does.  The main button that you will be interested is the 
'Add Date', clicking here will bring up a requester asking for the date.
Unfortunately at the moment there is no way to choose from a calendar so
you need to type in the date in a particular format, for Anno it is:
the date, month (written) and year, like this: 14 May 2022.  After the 
year you can then add extra notes such as the place, person or event that
will take place.  Click on 'Okay' when you have typed in everything you 
need and it will appear in the main window.  That is pretty much to it, 
there is no way to set an alarm or sound notification on the day of the 
event at the moment though.  You can view the whole month with the 
appointment days highlighted by pressing on 'M' at the bottom of the 
screen, otherwise there is not much else you can do with the programme
aside from printing and saving your file.

For the moment Anno is a very simple and limited piece of software, I 
hope in the future the author will add some more features such as a sound
notification maybe on the day and the option to choose from a calendar 
instead of typing in the date.  Aside from these issues the software works
nicely and is something that I will be using on a daily basis.  It is a
real pleasure to see new programmes being made for the Amiga that help it
become a bit more useful in everyday life.  The Amiga still lives on 
thanks the efforts of people like Juergen Klawitter. 

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}			  
+ Simple and effective
+ Free	   
+ Does what it sets out to do
- Lack of useful features                                  
- GUI can be confusing for the first time user 
@endnode

@node powersupplyreview
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*Amiga Power Supply Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
OLED Digital Display Power Supply for the A500/A600 and A1200

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
www.ebay.com - £49.99 + shipping
Seller: keelog

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}We All Need Power@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
The standard power supplies that came with our Amigas are beginning to
look a bit long in the tooth.  Some just refuse to turn on or are not
giving your Amiga the proper power it needs.  It is possible to try and
fix them but for most users we are happy to buy a replacement.  Of recent
there have been quite a few replacement PSUs available, some using a ATX 
power supply which is quite bulky but gives you the power for you Amiga 
and all it's expansions.  Others are smaller but no less powerful, it was
for this case that I was looking for a replacement PSU, it had to be 100v
since my Amiga resides in Japan and if possible not too large but capable
of powering my A1200 with its various expansions.  I came across a power
supply sold it seems solely by the seller 'keelog', it is smaller than the
original A500 brick, has a touch sensor, OLED display and is available in 
110v.     

The listing states it provides a +5V DC, +12V DC, -12V DC and comes in 
black and grey.  I chose the grey version, the total cost including 
shipping to Japan was £54.98, not exactly cheap but pretty reasonable
considering it can only be used with an Amiga.  The seller quickly 
contacted me after purchase and shipped the item quickly, it took about
two weeks to arrive.  It was packed in a very strong cardboard box and 
had black foam on the inside, overall a very professional product.  The
plastic of the powersupply almost looks like it was 3D printed but is 
still very nice looking.  In particular I like the OLED that shows either
the Amiga logo or the up time of your Amiga and the current voltage.  
The plug has the typical US plug along with a third gound which means that 
if you are in Japan you will need an adapter, if I remember correctly in 
the States the wall sockets still have the third hole for ground.

Once I plugged in the adapter the plug into the A1200 fit nice and snuggly
so there is no chance of it falling out.  I turned on my A1200 and put it 
through it's paces, rendering Lightwave animations, playing 3D games,
listening to MP3s and audio editing.  The Amiga never once froze or seemed
unstable, the power supply itself got a little warm but I would not say 
uncomfortably hot like you get with the Apple chargers, those things can 
be too hot to touch at times.  Now it must be noted that this PSU did not 
work so well with the ACA1221lc if you run it at 40mhz, Jens has mentioned 
that you need a particular type of power supply and apparently this is not 
one them.  If you run the card up 28mhz you will have no problems, but
moving beyond that you will end up with your Amiga locking and potentially
losing your hard disk data.  However when I overlocked my TF1260 up to 
62mhz I encountered no issues, I have been unable to overclock my TF1260
beyond that yet so I cannot say how well the power supply will work with
more overclocking.

I believe this power supply should be enough for the needs of most users, 
if you have an ACA1221lc and want to run it at 40mhz then you will need to 
look somewhere else.  The small OLED display is quite charming and it is 
nice to see how much time I have spent (wasted?) on the Amiga.  It is small 
enough to hide behind the Amiga or desk without taking up too much space
and the cables are long enough so as the PSU can sit on the floor whilst
still reaching your Amiga.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Final Thoughts@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Bottom line, if you are looking for a well put together power supply that 
can meet the needs of your expanded Amiga, looks good, is small and has 
the added benefit of a small display then this is a good choice to go 
with.  There are other power supplies available, so you should always have
a look however this is one of the best power supplies I have had for my
Amiga, and if I ever can afford another orginal Amiga I would buy some 
it again.
     
@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}			  
+ Works very nicely
+ Does not get too hot	   
+ OLED display suprisingly useful
- Uses a three prong plug for 100v countries                                  
@endnode

