@node msmadlemon "Ms Mad Lemon a.k.a Maddi Interview"
@toc amigaspeak
@{b}1.  On your Twitter and YouTube channel you have a variety of videos about
the Amiga and other electronics.  What got you first interested in 
electronics and the Amiga?@{ub}

My interest in Amiga began at around seven years old when my brother got 
an Amiga 500 back in around 1989, The first thing I saw on it was Avenger 
Megademo. I spent a lot of time on it, initially with games, but then 
eventually on things like deluxe paint II which brought out my creative 
side further. 

Electronics I got into around a similar age where I first found a motor 
and connected a battery to it, it then began, I started connecting a 
battery to everything that had two legs, light bulbs, LEDs even a resistor 
(not sure what I was expecting it to do) Then the three legged spider 
(transistor) confused me. Where do I connect the battery?! Years went on 
and so did my electronics.

@{b}2.  You are very creative, making music, art, photography and building 
projects, if you had to choose to do one, which you most prefer?@{ub}

Oh that is a very difficult question. Right now I'm in the music creating 
mode and would choose music as it would let me use an Amiga, however, I 
know in a couple of months I'l probably start doing photography or 
something else. Whatever mode I'm in, whatever I'm doing becomes my whole 
world. If I was pushed to choose it would probably be photography or 
making music. Tough question!

@{b}3.  Do you think owning an Amiga helped in nurturing your interest in 
computer graphics and music?@{ub}

Definitely! I got a Casio SK-1 sampling keyboard when I was little which 
started something off. Imitating tunes which I already knew. But treated 
as a toy really, it wouldn't have gone much further. So here comes the 
Amiga and pulls me into this world of hours and hours of music creation. 
I'd say the Amiga not only helped in nurturing, but gave me a platform. 
With regards to graphics, it's definitely Deluxe Paint II on the Amiga 
which got me into that side of things.

@{b}4.  You have released two albums in 2020, Memories and Waterfall, what 
Amiga hardware did you use to make the albums?@{ub}

Actually these two albums may be released in 2020, but most of the tracks 
I created on an Amiga in the 1990s using Soundtracker Pro 2. In fact all 
of the tracks on the album 'Waterfall' are from the 1990s and early 2000s.
The album 'Memorias' has got tracks I created in recent years but on the 
Amiga, exactly the way I did back in the 90s. There is an upcoming album
'Zaman' which will also have a couple of tracks from the 1990s but all the 
same, created on the Amiga using Soundtracker Pro 2. 

@{b}5.  What did you find easy and difficult about making the album on an 
Amiga?@{ub}

Its difficult because it's very different from conventional way of music 
creation or songwriting and you have to learn the concept of the tracker 
and how everything works, to piece together segments.

Easy because you can do everything at your own pace if you wish, there's 
no need for rehearsing, no issues with timing or sync. 

@{b}6.  What is your process when making a track?@{ub}

I start of messing around on a musical keyboard or synthesizer, just 
playing what sounds right, if I get a melody, I play it onto the Tracker 
and then build a chord progression around it, then a beat and bassline. 
Other times I have a chord progression and then build a beat and bassline 
around it, then create a melody around that. 

@{b}7.  The tracks on Memorias sounds reminiscent of the early 90s demos, was
this intentional?@{ub}

I've had similar comments about my latest track 'Mirrors' sounding 
Kraftwerk-esque. Quite a compliment actually! But neither was intentional, 
I'm just into that kind of music. I don't listen to modern music much at 
all. I listen to a lot of Amiga music, C64 SID, and anything from back in 
the day. Basically I just create what naturally comes to me or how I feel, 
I don't aim for it to sound like it's from back in the day or something 
specific. Perhaps it's me who is still stuck in the 1980s-1990s

@{b}8.  In your videos you are creating music in ProTracker, have you used any 
other trackers or music software on the Amiga?@{ub}

I create music on Soundtracker Pro 2, which works pretty much like 
Protracker but has it's own proprietary MOD format, which unfortunately is 
incompatible with MOD because it can do a few more things. However the 
basic principle is pretty much the same. 

Mostly yes, I create music on Soundtracker Pro 2. I've tried using Octamed 
but I cant get on with the interface, I've had a few people tell me that 
Octamed 4 is the one to try, Octamed 5 and above had been changed and is 
apparently more confusing for many.

@{b}9.  Are there any Amiga musicians that you have take influence from?@{ub}

I wouldn't say direct influence, but I suppose what you enjoy listening to 
would have a natural influence on your creativity.  Though my track 
'Waterfall' is a direct influence from Matthew Simmonds (4-Mat) track 
'Waterfall'. I sort of fell in love with that track of his for some reason 
and just wanted to do my own take of it.
 
Other artists I enjoy listening to are 'Pic Saint Loup', Chris Hulsbeck, 
but there's too many to list. I like quite a mixture, so I listen to many 
artists rather than a specific few.

@{b}10.  Is there anything that you have not tried on the Amiga i.e. software 
or hardware and would like to do in the future?@{ub}

I haven't tried much of video work, using Genlocks or frame grabbers. I've 
always wanted to so I may try some of that at some point. 

@{b}11.  The Amiga has been gaining in popularity again with the A500 MINI 
coming out this year, why do you think there has been an increase in 
interest in the Amiga platform?@{ub}

There seems to be a wave of people looking back at the past and feeling 
nostalgia for lost years. Frankly I never left these years and always 
lived feeling Nostalgic. I held onto my Amigas until around 2005-2006 and 
only sold my stuff because I thought I had to, that is a huge regret I 
have, but I have everything back now.
 
I can understand why people look back, there seems to be a movement going 
on to bring back elements of the past. Amiga being a big one in many 
people's lives. This has been going on for a few years though, I'm 
surprised the A500 MINI has only just come out now. 

@{b}12.  You had an interesting video about PD games, since we do not cover 
games, can you tell us what is your favourite non-game PD software?@{ub}

Well, Soundtracker Pro 2 :o) But also Diskmaster 2 and X-Copy.

@{b}13.  What would be your dream Amiga setup and what would you like to see 
in a future Amiga if one was ever released?@{ub}

A future Amiga. Well back in the day I would have said a towered Amiga, 
but over time I've fallen in love with the original desktop A500/A1200 
form factor. 

Okay I'm going to let myself go crazy now when answering this question..
I'd love to have an Amiga which resembles the original A500 or A1200, with 
a DVD drive and floppy built in (Kickstart ROMs that can boot directly 
from CD/DVD). USB ports. Fast IDE.

To have graphics and video that can upscale the standard RGB output 
resolutions but also have an RTG mode and high graphics/chip RAM. 

For it to be switchable between three modes: 
A500 kick1.3 stock mode. A1200 AGA Kick 3+ stock mode. A1200 accelerated 
mode with FPU and switchable PPC mode so that I can finally try Amiga 
OS4.1 on a classic Amiga :o). 

The ability to be able to choose the amount of fast RAM to have in all 
three modes. An updated Paula chip (which really should have been done on 
the A1200)

Okay, my ideal Soundchip would be a Paula+SID hybrid, 4-8 Paula Channels 
(with 8-16bit sampling) + 3-6 SID Channels with both 6581 R4 filters and 
8580.

And a version of Soundtracker Pro 2 which can deal with all this including 
the SID Channels and synthesis. I would be in heaven!! :o))

@{b}14.  Thank you Maddi for taking the time to answer our questions, is 
there anything you would like to say to our readers or about your future 
projects?@{ub}

Well, one thing I've not got is a shortage of ideas for videos and future 
projects, there is a lot lined up, so do check out my Youtube channel and 
all what I do. 

Thank you for including me in your magazine!
@endnode
@node karljeacle "Karl Jeacle Interiew"
@toc amigaspeak
@{b}1. Karl, can you please tell us a little about you, where you come from, 
what you do, etc?@{ub}

I live in Dublin, Ireland and have been working in the telecoms and ISP 
business for almost 30 years.

@{b}2. You are the programmer for the AmiGemini protocol browser,before 
we get into that project can you tell us how you started with computers?@{ub}

My first computer was a ZX Spectrum 48K. I played games and learned how to 
program in BASIC. I upgraded to the +2 and +3 models but my first serious 
computer was an Atari PC3 8088. I bought a PC because I thought that's 
what grown-ups used. It was good to learn about DOS and how PCs worked but 
when I saw my friends' Amigas, I sold my PC and bought an Amiga 2000 with 
a bridgeboard. The bridgeboard was handy but ultimately it was the Amiga 
that was used the most.

@{b}3. What attracted you to programming?@{ub}

I used to type in the programs in the computer magazines in the 1980s. In 
those days there were lots of books and magazines teaching you how to 
program in BASIC on your 8-bit home computer. When you got bored of 
playing games, it was fun to make your computer do other things.

@{b}4. What other projects have you worked on the Amiga before AmiGemini?@{ub}

In the 1990s, I wrote a book called First Steps Amiga Surfin - a guide to 
getting online with the Amiga. A couple of years ago, I wrote AmiSpeedTest 
- a program to measure your Amiga's download speed on the Internet. As you 
can see, there's a sort of networking theme developing here.

@{b}5. Why do you programme for the Amiga, and what other platforms do you 
develop for?@{ub}

At work I use Python a lot. It's a great language for quickly building all 
kinds of projects. Outside of work, I have an Android app that's written in 
Java, and there's an iOS port written in Typescript. While these are 
popular modern languages, they are all very high level. You take for 
granted the layers of libraries and abstractions. Programming in C on the 
Amiga with no memory protection is like an antidote to this. And learning 
about the 68K reminds you how computers actually work. 

@{b}6. The Gemini protocol was created in 2019, can you explain what the Gemini 
protocol is?@{ub}

It's like a simpler text-only version of the Web. Instead of Web servers, 
there are Gemini capsules. Instead of TCP port 443, there is TCP port 1965. 
Instead of HTML, there is Gemtext, a markup language that's closer to 
Markdown than HTML. Instead of CSS? Nothing. It's up to the client browser 
to layout pages in a user-friendly way. As for Javascript, that's a 
non-starter.

In common with Gopher it is text-only, but like today's Web, it uses 
modern encryption to secure connections. Privacy is one of the motivations 
behind Gemini. Many Gemini users were growing wary of the amount of 
tracking that takes place on web sites today. There is no place for that 
in Gemini. 

There are no cookies or other tracking devices. Requests have no headers 
with extra information that can identify the user agent. The server only 
sees the page request and its source IP address.

@{b}7. What drove you to create the AmiGemini programme?@{ub}

In addition to being a nice hobby project to work on the Amiga, I thought 
that Gemini could be a good fit for the Amiga. The requirement for TLS 
encryption does require some CPU power but the rest of Gemini is simple 
enough that it's possible to browse Geminispace on an Amiga 1200.

@{b}8. What benefits does the Gemini protocol offer to Amiga users?@{ub}

It's a relatively lightweight way to browse content on the Internet. There 
is a small but growing amount of Amiga content available. At the time of 
writing there are Gemini mirrors of the latest files on Aminet and the 
latest Amiga Future news.

@{b}9. What would you like to implement in the future releases?@{ub}

I would like to make sure AmiGemini implements most, if not all, of the 
Gemini specification and supports any future developments. I have a few 
ideas for new features and have had some good feedback so if I don't get 
too busy on other projects hopefully I'll be able to develop it further.

@{b}10. Do think that Gemini protocol has a future or will be forgotten about 
in 10 years time?@{ub}

The web is getting heavier and heavier and so there is a growing "small 
web" movement. I don't know if Gemini will still be around in 10 years but 
Gopher is still alive after 30 years. It's likely that there will be some 
form of text-based protocol that will be in common use.

@{b}11. Do you have any other ideas for new Amiga software?@{ub}
Nothing at the moment but who knows what the future holds?

@{b}12. What Amiga computers do you have and do you develop your software on 
the Amiga?@{ub}

I have a small collection of Amigas but my original A4000 is my primary
machine. I do all of my testing on the A4000 but I use my FreeBSD desktop 
for development work.

@{b}13. Thank you for your time Karl, is there anything else you would like to 
say or add about yourself, the Gemini protocol or about Amigas?@{ub}

I would like to say thanks to everyone who has helped test and provide 
feedback about AmiGemini. I would also like to thank Frank Wille and Oliver 
Roberts for their respective work on VBCC and AmiSSL. Without these great 
pieces of Amiga software AmiGemini would not exist.
@endnode

